# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: population-genetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The mathematical theory of the coalescent was developed independently by several groups in the early 1980s as a natural extension of classical population genetics theory and models, but can be primarily attributed to John Kingman.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Advances in coalescent theory include recombination, selection, overlapping generations and virtually any arbitrarily complex evolutionary or demographic model in population genetic analysis.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The model can be used to produce many theoretical genealogies, and then compare observed data to these simulations to test assumptions about the demographic history of a population.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Coalescent theory can be used to make inferences about population genetic parameters, such as migration, population size and recombination.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Consider a single gene locus sampled from two haploid individuals in a population.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The ancestry of this sample is traced backwards in time to the point where these two lineages *coalesce* in their most recent common ancestor (MRCA).
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Coalescent theory seeks to estimate the expectation of this time period and its variance.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The probability that two lineages coalesce in the immediately preceding generation is the probability that they share a parental DNA sequence.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] In a population with a constant effective population size with 2*Ne* copies of each locus, there are 2*Ne* "potential parents" in the previous generation.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Under a random mating model, the probability that two alleles originate from the same parental copy is thus 1/(2*Ne*) and, correspondingly, the probability that they do *not* coalesce is 1 − 1/(2*Ne*).
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] This is mathematically convenient, as the standard exponential distribution has both the expected value and the standard deviation equal to 2*Ne*.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Therefore, although the *expected* time to coalescence is 2*Ne*, actual coalescence times have a wide range of variation.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Note that coalescent time is the number of preceding generations where the coalescence took place and not calendar time, though an estimation of the latter can be made multiplying 2*Ne* with the average time between generations.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The mathematical object one formally obtains by letting *Ne* go to infinity is known as the Kingman coalescent.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Coalescent theory can also be used to model the amount of variation in DNA sequences expected from genetic drift and mutation.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] This value is termed the mean heterozygosity, represented as ${\bar {H}}$ .
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Mean heterozygosity is calculated as the probability of a mutation occurring at a given generation divided by the probability of any "event" at that generation (either a mutation or a coalescence).
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The probability that the event is a mutation is the probability of a mutation in either of the two lineages: $2\mu$ .
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] For $4N_{e}\mu \gg 1$ , the vast majority of allele pairs have at least one difference in nucleotide sequence.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] There are numerous extensions to the coalescent model, such as the Λ-coalescent which allows for the possibility of multifurcations.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Coalescents can be visualised using dendrograms which show the relationship of branches of the population to each other.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The point where two branches meet indicates a coalescent event.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] A considerable number of human diseases can be attributed to genetics, from simple Mendelian diseases like sickle-cell anemia and cystic fibrosis, to more complicated maladies like cancers and mental illnesses.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The latter are polygenic diseases, controlled by multiple genes that may occur on different chromosomes, but diseases that are precipitated by a single abnormality are relatively simple to pinpoint and trace – although not so simple that this has been achieved for all diseases.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] It is immensely useful in understanding these diseases and their processes to know where they are located on chromosomes, and how they have been inherited through generations of a family, as can be accomplished through coalescent analysis.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Genetic diseases are passed from one generation to another just like other genes.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] While any gene may be shuffled from one chromosome to another during homologous recombination, it is unlikely that one gene alone will be shifted.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Thus, other genes that are close enough to the disease gene to be linked to it can be used to trace it.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Polygenic diseases have a genetic basis even though they don't follow Mendelian inheritance models, and these may have relatively high occurrence in populations, and have severe health effects.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Such diseases may have incomplete penetrance, and tend to be polygenic*,* complicating their study.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] These traits may arise due to many small mutations, which together have a severe and deleterious effect on the health of the individual.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Linkage mapping methods, including Coalescent theory can be put to work on these diseases, since they use family pedigrees to figure out which markers accompany a disease, and how it is inherited.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] At the very least, this method helps narrow down the portion, or portions, of the genome on which the deleterious mutations may occur.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Complications in these approaches include epistatic effects, the polygenic nature of the mutations, and environmental factors.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] That said, genes whose effects are additive carry a fixed risk of developing the disease, and when they exist in a disease genotype, they can be used to predict risk and map the gene.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Both the regular coalescent and the shattered coalescent (which allows that multiple mutations may have occurred in the founding event, and that the disease may occasionally be triggered by environmental factors) have been put to work in understanding disease genes.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Studies have been carried out correlating disease occurrence in fraternal and identical twins, and the results of these studies can be used to inform coalescent modeling.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Since identical twins share all of their genome, but fraternal twins only share half their genome, the difference in correlation between the identical and fraternal twins can be used to work out if a disease is heritable, and if so how strongly.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The human single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) map has revealed large regional variations in heterozygosity, more so than can be explained on the basis of (Poisson-distributed) random chance.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] In part, these variations could be explained on the basis of assessment methods, the availability of genomic sequences, and possibly the standard coalescent population genetic model.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Population genetic influences could have a major influence on this variation: some loci presumably would have comparatively recent common ancestors, others might have much older genealogies, and so the regional accumulation of SNPs over time could be quite different.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] The local density of SNPs along chromosomes appears to cluster in accordance with a variance to mean power law and to obey the Tweedie compound Poisson distribution.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] Coalescent theory is a natural extension of the more classical population genetics concept of neutral evolution and is an approximation to the Fisher–Wright (or Wright–Fisher) model for large populations.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] It was discovered independently by several researchers in the 1980s.
[src:population-genetics/coalescent-theory] A large body of software exists for both simulating data sets under the coalescent process as well as inferring parameters such as population size and migration rates from genetic data.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The **effective population size** (*N**e*) is the size of an idealised population that would experience the same rate of genetic drift as the real population.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Idealised populations are those where each locus evolves independently, following the assumptions of the neutral theory of molecular evolution.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The effective population size is normally smaller than the census population size *N*.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This can be due to chance events prevent some individuals from breeding, to occasional population bottlenecks, to background selection, and to genetic hitchhiking.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The same real population could have a different effective population size for different properties of interest, such as genetic drift (or more precisely, the speed of coalescence) over one generation vs. over many generations.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Within a species, areas of the genome that have more genes and/or less genetic recombination tend to have lower effective population sizes, because of the effects of selection at linked sites.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] In a population with selection at many loci and abundant linkage disequilibrium, the coalescent effective population size may not reflect the census population size at all, or may reflect its logarithm.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The concept of effective population size was introduced in the field of population genetics in 1931 by the American geneticist Sewall Wright.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Some versions of the effective population size are used in wildlife conservation.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] In a rare experiment that directly measured genetic drift one generation at a time, in *Drosophila* populations of census size 16, the effective population size was 11.5.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This measurement was achieved through studying changes in the frequency of a neutral allele from one generation to another in over 100 replicate populations.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] More commonly, effective population size is estimated indirectly by comparing data on current within-species genetic diversity to theoretical expectations.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] According to the neutral theory of molecular evolution, an idealised diploid population will have a pairwise nucleotide diversity equal to 4 $\mu$ *N**e*, where $\mu$ is the mutation rate.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The effective population size can therefore be estimated empirically by dividing the nucleotide diversity by 4 $\mu$ .
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This captures the cumulative effects of genetic drift, genetic hitchhiking, and background selection over longer timescales.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] More advanced methods, permitting a changing effective population size over time, have also been developed.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The effective size measured to reflect these longer timescales may have little relationship to the number of individuals physically present in a population.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Measured effective population sizes vary between genes in the same population, being low in genome areas of low recombination and high in genome areas of high recombination.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Sojourn times are proportional to N in neutral theory, but for alleles under selection, sojourn times are proportional to log(N).
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Genetic hitchhiking can cause neutral mutations to have sojourn times proportional to log(N): this may explain the relationship between measured effective population size and the local recombination rate.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] If the recombination map of recombination frequencies along chromosomes is known, *N**e* can be inferred from *r*P2 = 1 / (1+4*N**e* *r*), where *r*P is the Pearson correlation coefficient between loci.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This expression can be interpreted as the probability that two lineages coalesce before one allele on either lineage recombines onto some third lineage.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The population size might not be constant over time, and thus neither might the effective population size (defined as coalescence speed).
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] With a constant population size, we expect larger pairwise Hamming distance between sequences to be rarer.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Under population expansion, an intermediate Hamming distance is instead most common; this is seen for humans.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] A skyline plot more directly describes coalescence speed over time.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The pairwise sequential Markovian coalescent and multiple sequential Markovian coalescent take the average of skyline plots over many loci.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] An alternative approach infers effective population size over time, together with migration among populations, using the allele frequency spectrum, describing how often alleles are rare versus common.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Yet another approach exploits runs of homozygosity to incorporate information from recombination events.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] A survey of publications on 102 mostly wildlife animal and plant species yielded 192 *N**e*/*N* ratios.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Seven different estimation methods were used in the surveyed studies.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Accordingly, the ratios ranged widely from 10*-6* for Pacific oysters to 0.994 for humans, with an average of 0.34 across the examined species.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Based on these data they subsequently estimated more comprehensive ratios, accounting for fluctuations in population size, variance in family size and unequal sex-ratio.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] In an idealised Wright-Fisher model, the fate of an allele, beginning at an intermediate frequency, is largely determined by selection if the selection coefficient s ≫ 1/N, and largely determined by neutral genetic drift if s ≪ 1/N.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] In real populations, the cutoff value of s may depend instead on local recombination rates.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This limit to selection in a real population may be captured in a toy Wright-Fisher simulation through the appropriate choice of Ne.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The ability of a species to differentiate between nearly neutral alleles can be measured by how codon bias differs from neutral expectations.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The Ka/Ks ratio is also sometimes used as a proxy.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The drift-barrier hypothesis claims that populations with different selection effective population sizes are predicted to evolve profoundly different genome architectures.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This implied two potentially different effective population sizes, based either on the one-generation increase in variance across replicate populations **(variance effective population size)**, or on the one-generation change in the inbreeding coefficient **(inbreeding effective population size)**.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] These two are closely linked, and derived from F-statistics, but they are not identical.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Another important effective population size is the **selection effective population size** 1/scritical, where scritical is the critical value of the selection coefficient at which selection becomes more important than genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Let ${\widehat {\operatorname {var} }}(p'\mid p)$ denote the same, typically larger, variance in the actual population under consideration.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The variance effective population size $N_{e}^{(v)}$ is defined as the size of an idealized population with the same variance.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] In the following examples, one or more of the assumptions of a strictly idealised population are relaxed, while other assumptions are retained.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The variance effective population size of the more relaxed population model is then calculated with respect to the strict model.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Note this is less than the arithmetic mean of the population size, which in this example is 126.7.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The harmonic mean tends to be dominated by the smallest bottleneck that the population goes through.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] where *D* represents dioeciousness and may take the value 0 (for not dioecious) or 1 for dioecious.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] If population size is to remain constant, each individual must contribute on average two gametes to the next generation.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] An idealized population assumes that this follows a Poisson distribution so that the variance of the number of gametes contributed, *k* is equal to the mean number contributed, i.e.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] However, in natural populations the variance is often larger than this.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Note that if the variance of *k* is less than 2, *N**e* is greater than *N*.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] In the extreme case of a population experiencing no variation in family size, in a laboratory population in which the number of offspring is artificially controlled, *V**k* = 0 and *N**e* = 2*N*.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Where *N**m* is the number of males and *N**f* the number of females.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Again, this results in *N**e* being less than *N*.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The presentation follows Kempthorne (1957).
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] When organisms live longer than one breeding season, effective population sizes have to take into account the life tables for the species.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Assume a haploid population with discrete age structure.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] An example might be an organism that can survive several discrete breeding seasons.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] The number of newborn individuals per breeding season.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Similarly, the inbreeding effective number can be calculated for a diploid population with discrete age structure.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] This was first given by Johnson, but the notation more closely resembles Emigh and Pollak.
[src:population-genetics/effective-population-size] Assume the same basic parameters for the life table as given for the haploid case, but distinguishing between male and female, such as *N*0*ƒ* and *N*0*m* for the number of newborn females and males, respectively (notice lower case *ƒ* for females, compared to upper case *F* for inbreeding).
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] The **fixation index** (**FST**) is a measure of population differentiation due to genetic structure.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] It is frequently estimated from genetic polymorphism data, such as single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNP) or microsatellites.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Developed as a special case of Wright's F-statistics, it is one of the most commonly used statistics in population genetics.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Its values range from 0 to 1, with 0 being no differentiation and 1 being complete differentiation.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] This comparison of genetic variability within and between populations is frequently used in applied population genetics.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] A zero value implies complete panmixia; that is, that the two populations are interbreeding freely.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] A value of one implies that all genetic variation is explained by the population structure, and that the two populations do not share any genetic diversity.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] For idealized models such as Wright's finite island model, FST can be used to estimate migration rates.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] where m is the migration rate per generation, and $\mu$ is the mutation rate per generation.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] The interpretation of FST can be difficult when the data analyzed are highly polymorphic.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] In this case, the probability of identity by descent is very low and FST can have an arbitrarily low upper bound, which might lead to misinterpretation of the data.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Also, strictly speaking FST is not a distance in the mathematical sense, as it does not satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Two of the most commonly used definitions for FST at a given locus are based on 1) the variance of allele frequencies among populations, and on 2) the probability of identity by descent.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Wright's definition illustrates that FST measures the amount of genetic variance that can be explained by population structure.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] This can also be thought of as the fraction of total diversity that is not a consequence of the average diversity within subpopulations, where diversity is measured by the probability that two randomly selected alleles are different, namely $2p(1-p)$ .
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] where $f_{0}$ is the probability of identity by descent of two individuals given that the two individuals are in the same subpopulation, and ${\bar {f}}$ is the probability that two individuals from the total population are identical by descent.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Using this definition, FST can be interpreted as measuring how much closer two individuals from the same subpopulation are, compared to the total population.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] If the mutation rate is small, this interpretation can be made more explicit by linking the probability of identity by descent to coalescent times: Let T0 and T denote the average time to coalescence for individuals from the same subpopulation and the total population, respectively.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] This formulation has the advantage that the expected time to coalescence can easily be estimated from genetic data, which led to the development of various estimators for FST.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] In practice, none of the quantities used for the definitions can be easily measured.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] As a consequence, various estimators have been proposed.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] where $\pi _{\text{Between}}$ and $\pi _{\text{Within}}$ represent the average number of pairwise differences between two individuals sampled from different sub-populations ( $\pi _{\text{Between}}$ ) or from the same sub-population ( $\pi _{\text{Within}}$ ).
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] The average pairwise difference within a population can be calculated as the sum of the pairwise differences divided by the number of pairs.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] However, this estimator is biased when sample sizes are small or if they vary between populations.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Therefore, more elaborate methods are used to compute FST in practice.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Two of the most widely used procedures are the estimator by Weir & Cockerham (1984), or performing an Analysis of molecular variance.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] A list of implementations is available at the end of this article.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] FST values depend strongly on the choice of populations.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Closely related ethnic groups, such as the Danes vs. the Dutch, or the Portuguese vs. the Spaniards show values significantly below 1%, indistinguishable from panmixia.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Within Europe, the most divergent ethnic groups have been found to have values of the order of 7% (Sámi vs.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Larger values are found if highly divergent homogenous groups are compared: the highest such value found was at close to 46%, between Mbuti and Papuans.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] In their study *The History and Geography of Human Genes (1994)*, Cavalli-Sforza, Menozzi and Piazza provide some of the most detailed and comprehensive estimates of genetic distances between human populations, within and across continents.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Their initial database contains 76,676 gene frequencies (using 120 blood polymorphisms), corresponding to 6,633 samples in different locations.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] By culling and pooling such samples, they restrict their analysis to 491 populations.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] They focus on *aboriginal populations* that were at their present location at the end of the 15th century when the great European migrations began.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] When studying genetic difference at the world level, the number is reduced to 42 representative populations, aggregating subpopulations characterized by a high level of genetic similarity.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] For these 42 populations, Cavalli-Sforza and coauthors report bilateral distances computed from 120 alleles.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] Among this set of 42 world populations, the greatest genetic distance observed is between Mbuti Pygmies and Papua New Guineans, where the Fst distance is 0.4573, while the smallest genetic distance (0.0021) is between the Danish and the English.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] When considering more disaggregated data for 26 European populations, the smallest genetic distance (0.0009) is between the Dutch and the Danes, and the largest (0.0667) is between the Lapps and the Sardinians.
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] The mean genetic distance among the 861 available pairings of the 42 selected populations was found to be 0.1338..
[src:population-genetics/fixation-index] It reported a value close to 12% between continental populations, and values close to panmixia (smaller than 1%) within continental populations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Genetic drift may cause alleles to disappear completely and thereby reduce genetic variation.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] It can also cause initially rare alleles to become much more frequent possibly leading to fixation where the initially rare allele displaces all others.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In the middle of the 20th century, vigorous debates occurred over the relative importance of natural selection versus neutral processes, including genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Ronald Fisher, who explained natural selection using Mendelian genetics, held the view that genetic drift plays at most a minor role in evolution, and this remained the dominant view for several decades.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The process of genetic drift can be illustrated using 20 marbles in a jar to represent 20 organisms in a population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Consider that jar of marbles as the starting population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Half of the marbles in the jar are red and half are blue, with each colour corresponding to a different allele of one gene in the population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In each new generation, the organisms reproduce at random.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] To represent this reproduction, randomly select a marble from the original jar and deposit a new marble with the same colour into a new jar.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This is the "offspring" of the original marble, meaning that the original marble remains in its jar.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Repeat this process until 20 new marbles are in the second jar.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The second jar will now contain 20 "offspring", or marbles of various colours.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Unless the second jar contains exactly 10 red marbles and 10 blue marbles, a random shift has occurred in the allele frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] If this process is repeated a number of times, the numbers of red and blue marbles picked each generation fluctuates.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Sometimes, a jar has more red marbles than its "parent" jar and sometimes more blue.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This fluctuation is analogous to genetic drift – a change in the population's allele frequency resulting from a random variation in the distribution of alleles from one generation to the next.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In any one generation, no marbles of a particular colour could be chosen, meaning they have no offspring.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In this example, if no red marbles are selected, the jar representing the new generation contains only blue offspring.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] If this happens, the red allele has been lost permanently in the population, while the remaining blue allele has become fixed: all future generations are entirely blue.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In small populations, fixation can occur in just a few generations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The mechanisms of genetic drift can be illustrated with a simple example.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Consider a very large colony of bacteria isolated in a drop of solution.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The bacteria are genetically identical except for a single gene with two alleles labeled **A** and **B**, which are neutral alleles, meaning that they do not affect the bacteria's ability to survive and reproduce; all bacteria in this colony are equally likely to survive and reproduce.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Suppose that half the bacteria have allele **A** and the other half have allele **B**.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Thus, **A** and **B** each has an allele frequency of 1/2.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The drop of solution then shrinks until it has only enough food to sustain four bacteria.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] All other bacteria die without reproducing.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Since all bacteria in the original solution are equally likely to survive when the solution shrinks, the four survivors are a random sample from the original colony.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] (The original population size is so large that the sampling effectively happens with replacement).
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In other words, each of the 16 possible allele combinations is equally likely to occur, with probability 1/16.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] As shown in the table, the total number of combinations that have the same number of **A** alleles as of **B** alleles is six, and the probability of this combination is 6/16.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The total number of other combinations is ten, so the probability of unequal number of **A** and **B** alleles is 10/16.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Thus, although the original colony began with an equal number of **A** and **B** alleles, quite possibly, the number of alleles in the remaining population of four members will not be equal.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The situation of equal numbers is actually less likely than unequal numbers.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In the latter case, genetic drift has occurred because the population's allele frequencies have changed due to random sampling.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In this example, the population contracted to just four random survivors, a phenomenon known as a population bottleneck.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] where *n=4* is the number of surviving bacteria.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Mathematical models of genetic drift can be designed using either branching processes or a diffusion equation describing changes in allele frequency in an idealised population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Consider a gene with two alleles, **A** or **B**.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In diploidy, populations consisting of *N* individuals have 2*N* copies of each gene.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] An individual can have two copies of the same allele or two different alleles.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The frequency of one allele is assigned *p* and the other *q*.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] where the symbol "**!**" signifies the factorial function.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The Moran model assumes overlapping generations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] At each time step, one individual is chosen to reproduce and one individual is chosen to die.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] So in each timestep, the number of copies of a given allele can go up by one, go down by one, or can stay the same.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This means that the transition matrix is tridiagonal, which means that mathematical solutions are easier for the Moran model than for the Wright–Fisher model.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] On the other hand, computer simulations are usually easier to perform using the Wright–Fisher model, because fewer time steps need to be calculated.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In the Moran model, it takes *N* timesteps to get through one generation, where *N* is the effective population size.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In the Wright–Fisher model, it takes just one.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In practice, the Moran and Wright–Fisher models give qualitatively similar results, but genetic drift runs twice as fast in the Moran model.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] If the variance in the number of offspring is much greater than that given by the binomial distribution assumed by the Wright–Fisher model, then given the same overall speed of genetic drift (the variance effective population size), genetic drift is a less powerful force compared to selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Even for the same variance, if higher moments of the offspring number distribution exceed those of the binomial distribution then again the force of genetic drift is substantially weakened.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Random changes in allele frequencies can also be caused by effects other than sampling error, for example random changes in selection pressure.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] One important alternative source of stochasticity, perhaps more important than genetic drift, is genetic draft.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Genetic draft is the effect on a locus by selection on linked loci.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The mathematical properties of genetic draft are different from those of genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The direction of the random change in allele frequency is autocorrelated across generations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The Hardy–Weinberg principle states that the distribution of two alleles in a diploid population will approximate a binomial distribution.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The overall frequency of alleles in this binomial distribution will remain constant from one generation to the next unless the it is disturbed by evolution.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Genetic drift is one mechanism of evolution that affects allele frequencies; the others are migration, genetic mutations, and natural selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The random sampling of alleles passed to the next generation (genetic drift) can cause an existing allele to disappear.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Because random sampling can remove, but not replace, an allele, and because random declines or increases in allele frequency influence expected allele distributions for the next generation, genetic drift drives a population towards genetic uniformity over time.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] When an allele reaches a frequency of 1 (100%) it is said to be "fixed" in the population and when an allele reaches a frequency of 0 (0%) it is lost.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Smaller populations achieve fixation faster, whereas in the limit of an infinite population, fixation is not achieved.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Once an allele becomes fixed, genetic drift comes to a halt, and the allele frequency cannot change unless a new allele is introduced in the population via mutation or gene flow.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Thus even while genetic drift is a random, directionless process, it acts to eliminate genetic variation over time.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Assuming genetic drift is the only evolutionary force acting on an allele, at any given time the probability that an allele will eventually become fixed in the population is simply its frequency in the population at that time.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] For example, if the frequency *p* for allele **A** is 75% and the frequency *q* for allele **B** is 25%, then given unlimited time the probability **A** will ultimately become fixed in the population is 75% and the probability that **B** will become fixed is 25%.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The expected number of generations for fixation to occur is proportional to the population size, such that fixation is predicted to occur much more rapidly in smaller populations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Normally the effective population size, which is smaller than the total population, is used to determine these probabilities.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The effective population (*N**e*) takes into account factors such as the level of inbreeding, the stage of the lifecycle in which the population is the smallest, and the fact that some neutral genes are genetically linked to others that are under selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The effective population size may not be the same for every gene in the same population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] where *T* is the number of generations, *N**e* is the effective population size, and *p* is the initial frequency for the given allele.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The result is the number of generations expected to pass before fixation occurs for a given allele in a population with given size (*N**e*) and allele frequency (*p*).
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] for the average number of generations expected before the loss of a neutral mutation in a population of actual size N.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The formulae above apply to an allele that is already present in a population, and which is subject to neither mutation nor natural selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] If an allele is lost by mutation much more often than it is gained by mutation, then mutation, as well as drift, may influence the time to loss.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The first approximation represents the waiting time until the first mutant destined for loss, with loss then occurring relatively rapidly by genetic drift, taking time ⁠1/*m*⁠ ≫ *N**e*.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The second approximation represents the time needed for deterministic loss by mutation accumulation.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In both cases, the time to fixation is dominated by mutation via the term ⁠1/*m*⁠, and is less affected by the effective population size.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In natural populations, genetic drift and natural selection do not act in isolation; both phenomena are always at play, together with mutation and migration.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Neutral evolution is the product of both mutation and drift, not of drift alone.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Similarly, even when selection overwhelms genetic drift, it can act only on variation that mutation provides.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] While natural selection has a direction, guiding evolution towards heritable adaptations to the current environment, genetic drift has no direction and is guided only by the mathematics of chance.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] As a result, drift acts upon the genotypic frequencies within a population without regard to their phenotypic effects.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In contrast, selection favors the spread of alleles whose phenotypic effects increase survival and/or reproduction of their carriers, lowers the frequencies of alleles that cause unfavorable traits, and ignores those that are neutral.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The law of large numbers predicts that when the absolute number of copies of the allele is small (e.g., in small populations), the magnitude of drift on allele frequencies per generation is larger.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The magnitude of drift is large enough to overwhelm selection at any allele frequency when the selection coefficient is less than 1 divided by the effective population size.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Non-adaptive evolution resulting from the product of mutation and genetic drift is therefore considered to be a consequential mechanism of evolutionary change primarily within small, isolated populations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The mathematics of genetic drift depend on the effective population size, but it is not clear how this is related to the actual number of individuals in a population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Genetic linkage to other genes that are under selection can reduce the effective population size experienced by a neutral allele.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] With a higher recombination rate, linkage decreases and with it this local effect on effective population size.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This effect is visible in molecular data as a correlation between local recombination rate and genetic diversity, and negative correlation between gene density and diversity at noncoding DNA regions.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Stochasticity associated with linkage to other genes that are under selection is not the same as sampling error, and is sometimes known as genetic draft in order to distinguish it from genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Low allele frequency makes alleles more vulnerable to being eliminated by random chance, even overriding the influence of natural selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] For example, while disadvantageous mutations are usually eliminated quickly within the population, new advantageous mutations are almost as vulnerable to loss through genetic drift as are neutral mutations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Not until the allele frequency for the advantageous mutation reaches a certain threshold will genetic drift have no effect.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] A population bottleneck is when a population contracts to a significantly smaller size over a short period of time due to some random environmental event.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In a true population bottleneck, the odds for survival of any member of the population are purely random, and are not improved by any particular inherent genetic advantage.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The bottleneck can result in radical changes in allele frequencies, completely independent of selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The impact of a population bottleneck can be sustained, even when the bottleneck is caused by a one-time event such as a natural catastrophe.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] An interesting example of a bottleneck causing unusual genetic distribution is the relatively high proportion of individuals with total rod cell color blindness (achromatopsia) on Pingelap atoll in Micronesia.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] After a bottleneck, inbreeding increases.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This increases the damage done by recessive deleterious mutations, in a process known as inbreeding depression.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The worst of these mutations are selected against, leading to the loss of other alleles that are genetically linked to them, in a process of background selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] For recessive harmful mutations, this selection can be enhanced as a consequence of the bottleneck, due to genetic purging.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This leads to a further loss of genetic diversity.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In addition, a sustained reduction in population size increases the likelihood of further allele fluctuations from drift in generations to come.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] A population's genetic variation can be greatly reduced by a bottleneck, and even beneficial adaptations may be permanently eliminated.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] There have been many known cases of population bottleneck in the recent past.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Prior to the arrival of Europeans, North American prairies were habitat for millions of greater prairie chickens.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In Illinois alone, their numbers plummeted from about 100 million birds in 1900 to about 50 birds in the 1990s.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The declines in population resulted from hunting and habitat destruction, but a consequence has been a loss of most of the species' genetic diversity.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] DNA analysis comparing birds from the mid century to birds in the 1990s documents a steep decline in the genetic variation in just the latter few decades.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Currently the greater prairie chicken is experiencing low reproductive success.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] However, the genetic loss caused by bottleneck and genetic drift can increase fitness, as in *Ehrlichia*.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Over-hunting also caused a severe population bottleneck in the northern elephant seal in the 19th century.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Their resulting decline in genetic variation can be deduced by comparing it to that of the southern elephant seal, which were not so aggressively hunted.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The founder effect is a special case of a population bottleneck, occurring when a small group in a population splinters off from the original population and forms a new one.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The random sample of alleles in the just formed new colony is expected to grossly misrepresent the original population in at least some respects.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] It is even possible that the number of alleles for some genes in the original population is larger than the number of gene copies in the founders, making complete representation impossible.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] When a newly formed colony is small, its founders can strongly affect the population's genetic make-up far into the future.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] A well-documented example is found in the Amish migration to Pennsylvania in 1744.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Two members of the new colony shared the recessive allele for Ellis–Van Creveld syndrome.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Members of the colony and their descendants tend to be religious isolates and remain relatively insular.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] As a result of many generations of inbreeding, Ellis–Van Creveld syndrome is now much more prevalent among the Amish than in the general population.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The difference in gene frequencies between the original population and colony may also trigger the two groups to diverge significantly over the course of many generations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] As the difference, or genetic distance, increases, the two separated populations may become distinct, both genetically and phenetically, although not only genetic drift but also natural selection, gene flow, and mutation contribute to this divergence.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] This potential for relatively rapid changes in the colony's gene frequency led most scientists to consider the founder effect (and by extension, genetic drift) a significant driving force in the evolution of new species.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Sewall Wright was the first to attach this significance to random drift and small, newly isolated populations with his shifting balance theory of speciation.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Following after Wright, Ernst Mayr created many persuasive models to show that the decline in genetic variation and small population size following the founder effect were critically important for new species to develop.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] However, there is much less support for this view today since the hypothesis has been tested repeatedly through experimental research and the results have been equivocal at best.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The role of random chance in evolution was first outlined by Arend L.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Hagedoorn and Anna Cornelia Hagedoorn-Vorstheuvel La Brand in 1921.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] They highlighted that random survival plays a key role in the loss of variation from populations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Fisher (1922) responded to this with the first, albeit marginally incorrect, mathematical treatment of the "Hagedoorn effect".
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Notably, he expected that many natural populations were too large (an N ~10,000) for the effects of drift to be substantial and thought drift would have an insignificant effect on the evolutionary process.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The corrected mathematical treatment and term "genetic drift" was later coined by a founder of population genetics, Sewall Wright.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] His first use of the term "drift" was in 1929, though at the time he was using it in the sense of a directed process of change, or natural selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Random drift by means of sampling error came to be known as the "Sewall–Wright effect", though he was never entirely comfortable to see his name given to it.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Wright referred to all changes in allele frequency as either "steady drift" (e.g., selection) or "random drift" (e.g., sampling error).
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] "Drift" came to be adopted as a technical term in the stochastic sense exclusively.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Today it is usually defined still more narrowly, in terms of sampling error, although this narrow definition is not universal.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Wright wrote that the "restriction of "random drift" or even "drift" to only one component, the effects of accidents of sampling, tends to lead to confusion".
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Sewall Wright considered the process of random genetic drift by means of sampling error equivalent to that by means of inbreeding, but later work has shown them to be distinct.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In the early days of the modern evolutionary synthesis, scientists were beginning to blend the new science of population genetics with Charles Darwin's theory of natural selection.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Within this framework, Wright focused on the effects of inbreeding on small relatively isolated populations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] He introduced the concept of an adaptive landscape in which phenomena such as cross breeding and genetic drift in small populations could push them away from adaptive peaks, which in turn allow natural selection to push them towards new adaptive peaks.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Wright thought smaller populations were more suited for natural selection because "inbreeding was sufficiently intense to create new interaction systems through random drift but not intense enough to cause random nonadaptive fixation of genes".
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Wright's views on the role of genetic drift in the evolutionary scheme were controversial almost from the very beginning.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] One of the most vociferous and influential critics was colleague Ronald Fisher.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Fisher conceded genetic drift played some role in evolution, but an insignificant one.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Fisher has been accused of misunderstanding Wright's views because in his criticisms Fisher seemed to argue Wright had rejected selection almost entirely.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] To Fisher, viewing the process of evolution as a long, steady, adaptive progression was the only way to explain the ever-increasing complexity from simpler forms.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] But the debates have continued between the "gradualists" and those who lean more toward the Wright model of evolution where selection and drift together play an important role.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] In 1968, Motoo Kimura rekindled the debate with his neutral theory of molecular evolution, which claims that most of the genetic changes are caused by genetic drift acting on neutral mutations.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] The role of genetic drift by means of sampling error in evolution has been criticized by John H.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Provine, who argue that selection on linked sites is a more important stochastic force.
[src:population-genetics/genetic-drift] Emerging in the 1990s, constructive neutral evolution used genetic drift to theorize how complex systems emerge through neutral transitions.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] These influences include *genetic drift*, *mate choice*, *assortative mating*, *natural selection*, *sexual selection*, *mutation*, *gene flow*, *meiotic drive*, *genetic hitchhiking*, *population bottleneck*, *founder effect,* *inbreeding and outbreeding depression*.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] In the absence of selection, mutation, genetic drift, or other forces, allele frequencies *p* and *q* are constant between generations, so equilibrium is reached.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Hardy and Wilhelm Weinberg, who first demonstrated it mathematically.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Hardy's paper was focused on debunking the view that a dominant allele would automatically tend to increase in frequency (a view possibly based on a misinterpreted question at a lecture).
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Today, tests for Hardy–Weinberg genotype frequencies are used primarily to test for population stratification and other forms of non-random mating.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Consider a population of monoecious diploids, where each organism produces male and female gametes at equal frequency, and has two alleles at each gene locus.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] We assume that the population is so large that it can be treated as infinite.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Organisms reproduce by random union of gametes (the "gene pool" population model).
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] A locus in this population has two alleles, A and a, that occur with initial frequencies *f*0(A) = *p* and *f*0(a) = *q*, respectively.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The different ways to form genotypes for the next generation can be shown in a Punnett square, where the proportion of each genotype is equal to the product of the row and column allele frequencies from the current generation.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The sum of the entries is *p*2 + 2*pq* + *q*2 = 1, as the genotype frequencies must sum to one.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Note again that as *p* + *q* = 1, the binomial expansion of (*p* + *q*)2 = *p*2 + 2*pq* + *q*2 = 1 gives the same relationships.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] These frequencies define the Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] It should be mentioned that the genotype frequencies after the first generation need not equal the genotype frequencies from the initial generation, e.g.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] However, the genotype frequencies for all *future* times will equal the Hardy–Weinberg frequencies, e.g.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] and constructs a Punnett square for each, so as to calculate its contribution to the next generation's genotypes.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] These contributions are weighted according to the probability of each diploid–diploid combination, which follows a multinomial distribution with *k* = 3.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] For example, the probability of the mating combination (AA,aa) is 2 *f**t*(AA)*f**t*(aa) and it can only result in the Aa genotype: [0,1,0].
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] As before, one can show that the allele frequencies at time *t* + 1 equal those at time *t*, and so, are constant in time.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Similarly, the genotype frequencies depend only on the allele frequencies, and so, after time *t* = 1 are also constant in time.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] If in either monoecious or dioecious organisms, either the allele or genotype proportions are initially unequal in either sex, it can be shown that constant proportions are obtained after one generation of random mating.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Violations of the Hardy–Weinberg assumptions can cause deviations from expectation.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] How this affects the population depends on the assumptions that are violated.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] If a population violates one of the following four assumptions, the population may continue to have Hardy–Weinberg proportions each generation, but the allele frequencies will change over time.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] In real world genotype data, deviations from Hardy–Weinberg Equilibrium may be a sign of genotyping error.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Where the A gene is sex linked, the heterogametic sex (*e.g.*, mammalian males; avian females) have only one copy of the gene (and are termed hemizygous), while the homogametic sex (*e.g.*, human females) have two copies.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The genotype frequencies at equilibrium are *p* and *q* for the heterogametic sex but *p*2, 2*pq* and *q*2 for the homogametic sex.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] For example, in humans red–green colorblindness is an X-linked recessive trait.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] In western European males, the trait affects about 1 in 12, (*q* = 0.083) whereas it affects about 1 in 200 females (0.005, compared to *q*2 = 0.007), very close to Hardy–Weinberg proportions.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The population converges on equilibrium very quickly.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The simple derivation above can be generalized for more than two alleles and polyploidy.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Consider an extra allele frequency, *r*.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The two-allele case is the binomial expansion of (*p* + *q*)2, and thus the three-allele case is the trinomial expansion of (*p* + *q* + *r*)2.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The Hardy–Weinberg principle may also be generalized to polyploid systems, that is, for organisms that have more than two copies of each chromosome.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Whether the organism is a 'true' tetraploid or an amphidiploid will determine how long it will take for the population to reach Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Testing deviation from the HWP is generally performed using Pearson's chi-squared test, using the observed genotype frequencies obtained from the data and the expected genotype frequencies obtained using the HWP.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] For systems where there are large numbers of alleles, this may result in data with many empty possible genotypes and low genotype counts, because there are often not enough individuals present in the sample to adequately represent all genotype classes.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] If this is the case, then the asymptotic assumption of the chi-squared distribution, will no longer hold, and it may be necessary to use a form of Fisher's exact test, which requires a computer to solve.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Ford (1971) on the scarlet tiger moth, for which the phenotypes of a sample of the population were recorded.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Genotype–phenotype distinction is assumed to be negligibly small.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The null hypothesis is that the population is in Hardy–Weinberg proportions, and the alternative hypothesis is that the population is not in Hardy–Weinberg proportions.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] There is 1 degree of freedom (degrees of freedom for test for Hardy–Weinberg proportions are # genotypes − # alleles).
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The 5% significance level for 1 degree of freedom is 3.84, and since the χ2 value is less than this, the null hypothesis that the population is in Hardy–Weinberg frequencies is **not** rejected.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Fisher's exact test can be applied to testing for Hardy–Weinberg proportions.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Since the test is conditional on the allele frequencies, *p* and *q*, the problem can be viewed as testing for the proper number of heterozygotes.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] In this way, the hypothesis of Hardy–Weinberg proportions is rejected if the number of heterozygotes is too large or too small.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] where *n*11, *n*12, *n*22 are the observed numbers of the three genotypes, AA, Aa, and aa, respectively, and *n*1 is the number of A alleles, where $n_{1}=2n_{11}+n_{12}$ .
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Using this table, one must look up the significance level of the test based on the observed number of heterozygotes.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] For example, if one observed 20 heterozygotes, the significance level for the test is 0.007.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] As is typical for Fisher's exact test for small samples, the gradation of significance levels is quite coarse.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] However, a table like this has to be created for every experiment, since the tables are dependent on both *n* and *p*.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The equivalence tests are developed in order to establish sufficiently good agreement of the observed genotype frequencies and Hardy Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Let ${\mathcal {M}}$ denote the family of the genotype distributions under the assumption of Hardy Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The distance between a genotype distribution p and Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is defined by $d(p,{\mathcal {M}})=\min _{q\in {\mathcal {M}}}d(p,q)$ , where d is some distance.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The equivalence test problem is given by $H_{0}=\{d(p,{\mathcal {M}})\geq \varepsilon \}$ and $H_{1}=\{d(p,{\mathcal {M}})<\varepsilon \}$ , where $\varepsilon >0$ is a tolerance parameter.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] If the hypothesis $H_{0}$ can be rejected then the population is close to Hardy Weinberg equilibrium with a high probability.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The equivalence tests for the biallelic case are developed among others in Wellek (2004).
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The equivalence tests for the case of multiple alleles are proposed in Ostrovski (2020).
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The inbreeding coefficient, F (see also *F*-statistics), is one minus the observed frequency of heterozygotes over that expected from Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] For two alleles, the chi-squared goodness of fit test for Hardy–Weinberg proportions is equivalent to the test for inbreeding, $F=0$ .
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The inbreeding coefficient is unstable as the expected value approaches zero, and thus not useful for rare and very common alleles.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Mendelian genetics were rediscovered in 1900.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] However, it remained somewhat controversial for several years as it was not then known how it could cause continuous characteristics.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Udny Yule (1902) argued against Mendelism because he thought that dominant alleles would increase in the population.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Castle (1903) showed that without selection, the genotype frequencies would remain stable.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Karl Pearson (1903) found one equilibrium position with values of *p* = *q* = 0.5.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Reginald Punnett, unable to counter Yule's point, introduced the problem to G.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Hardy, a British mathematician, with whom he played cricket.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] To the Editor of Science: I am reluctant to intrude in a discussion concerning matters of which I have no expert knowledge, and I should have expected the very simple point which I wish to make to have been familiar to biologists.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Punnett has called my attention, suggest that it may still be worth making...
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Finally, suppose that the numbers are fairly large, so that mating may be regarded as random, that the sexes are evenly distributed among the three varieties, and that all are equally fertile.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The interesting question is: in what circumstances will this distribution be the same as that in the generation before?
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] may be, the distribution will in any case continue unchanged after the second generation.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The principle was thus known as *Hardy's law* in the English-speaking world until 1943, when Curt Stern pointed out that it had first been formulated independently in 1908 by the German physician Wilhelm Weinberg.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] William Castle in 1903 also derived the ratios for the special case of equal allele frequencies, and it is sometimes (but rarely) called the Hardy–Weinberg–Castle Law.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Hardy's statement begins with a recurrence relation for the frequencies *p*, 2*q*, and *r*.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] These recurrence relations follow from fundamental concepts in probability, specifically independence, and conditional probability.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] For example, consider the probability of an offspring from the generation $\textstyle t$ being homozygous dominant.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Alleles are inherited independently from each parent.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] A dominant allele can be inherited from a homozygous dominant parent with probability 1, or from a heterozygous parent with probability 0.5.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] To represent this reasoning in an equation, let $\textstyle A_{t}$ represent inheritance of a dominant allele from a parent.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Furthermore, let $\textstyle AA_{t-1}$ and $\textstyle Aa_{t-1}$ represent potential parental genotypes in the preceding generation.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The same reasoning, applied to the other genotypes yields the two remaining recurrence relations.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Equilibrium occurs when each proportion is constant between subsequent generations.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] By solving these equations necessary and sufficient conditions for equilibrium to occur can be determined.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Again, consider the frequency of homozygous dominant animals.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] First consider the case, where $\textstyle p_{t-1}=0$ , and note that it implies that $\textstyle q_{t-1}=0$ and $\textstyle r_{t-1}=1$ .
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] where the final equality holds because the allele proportions must sum to one.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] It can be shown that the other two equilibrium conditions imply the same equation.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Together, the solutions of the three equilibrium equations imply sufficiency of Hardy's condition for equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Since the condition always holds for the second generation, all succeeding generations have the same proportions.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] An example computation of the genotype distribution given by Hardy's original equations is instructive.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The phenotype distribution from Table 3 above will be used to compute Hardy's initial genotype distribution.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Note that the *p* and *q* values used by Hardy are not the same as those used above.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The reader may demonstrate that subsequent use of the second-generation values for a third generation will yield identical results.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The Hardy–Weinberg principle can also be used to estimate the frequency of carriers of an autosomal recessive condition in a population based on the frequency of suffers.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Let us assume an estimated $\textstyle {\frac {1}{2500}}$ babies are born with cystic fibrosis, this is about the frequency of homozygous individuals observed in Northern European populations.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] We can use the Hardy–Weinberg equations to estimate the carrier frequency, the frequency of heterozygous individuals, $\textstyle 2pq$ .
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] We therefore estimate the carrier rate to be $\textstyle {\frac {1}{25}}$ , which is about the frequency observed in Northern European populations.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] This can be simplified to the carrier frequency being about twice the square root of the birth frequency.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] It is possible to represent the distribution of genotype frequencies for a bi-allelic locus within a population graphically using a de Finetti diagram.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] This uses a triangular plot (also known as trilinear, triaxial or ternary plot) to represent the distribution of the three genotype frequencies in relation to each other.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] It differs from many other such plots in that the direction of one of the axes has been reversed.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The curved line in the diagram is the Hardy–Weinberg parabola and represents the state where alleles are in Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] It is possible to represent the effects of natural selection and its effect on allele frequency on such graphs.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] The de Finetti diagram was developed and used extensively by A.
[src:population-genetics/hardy-weinberg-principle] Edwards in his book *Foundations of Mathematical Genetics*.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] In defining LD, it is important first to distinguish two different concepts: linkage disequilibrium and linkage (genetic linkage).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Linkage disequilibrium refers to the association of genes *in a population.* Linkage, on the other hand, tells us whether genes are on the same chromosome *in an individual*.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] There is no necessary relationship between the two.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Genes that are closely linked may or may not be associated in populations.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Looking at parents and offspring, if genes at closely linked loci are present together in the parent, then they will usually be found together in the offspring.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] But looking at individuals in a population with no known common ancestry, it is much more difficult to see any relationships.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] To give a concrete, although imaginary, example in terms of frequencies of characters, consider a case where the "gene for red hair" is closely linked to the "gene for blue eyes".
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] What does that tell us about the expected population frequency of individuals with red hair and blue eyes?
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Are all redheads expected to have blue eyes, just because the genes controlling these characters are closely linked?
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Consider an allele *A* at the *A* locus with frequency *pA* in a particular population.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] At a linked *B* locus, the frequency of the allele *B* is *pB*.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The question is, what is the expected frequency *pAB* of the allele pair, or *haplotype*, *AB*?
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If the *A* and *B* alleles are independent in a population, then, by definition, *pAB* is simply the product *p*A*pB*.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Departure of *D* from zero indicates LD.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The descriptors "allele *A* at the *A* locus" and "allele *B* at the *B* locus" seem unnecessarily complicated.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Why not just the "*A* gene" and the "*B* gene"?
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The problem is that the term "gene" has been used since the foundation of genetics without a clear understanding of what a gene actually is.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] So, despite its widespread popular usage, its use is now avoided in genetics journals (see for a discussion about the changing definition of the gene).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This is unfortunate for discussions of population frequencies where the nature of the gene is not important.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Use of the term "allele" rather than "gene" sidesteps this problem, but in a way that is not entirely satisfactory.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Allele was originally defined and still understood as meaning "alternative", and allele *A* and allele *B* are not alleles (of each other).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The easiest way of talking about these linked "things" would be to use the term "gene".
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The expectation, dating back to 1918, is that LD is NOT to be expected, even for loci that are closely linked.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Robbins showed that recombination is expected to decrease the value of *D* in each generation by a factor (1 - *c*), where *c* is the frequency of recombination.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If there is some recombination, *c* will be greater than zero, *Dt* approaches zero as *t* becomes large.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] For the example given previously, no association is expected between hair colour and eye colour.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The frequency of individuals who are both red-headed and blue-eyed is expected to become simply the product of the frequency of red-headed individuals multiplied by the frequency of blue-eyed individuals, despite the fact that the two characters are controlled by closely linked loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Selection provides one possible way in which LD might be expected, in spite of the above argument.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If particular gene combinations are favoured, selection can cause LD to arise in the population, maintaining the frequency of the favoured gene combinations.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Such "equilibrium models" require reasonably high levels of selection, specifically "selective interaction", which is only possible for a minority of gene pairs.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The term LD remains as a legacy from this period.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] It was introduced for cases where there is known recombination but where the population has not come to equilibrium for the gene pair in question.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] But the most prominent uses of LD now involve very closely linked DNA bases (see below).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Independence cannot be expected in such cases.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The 'disequilibrium' description seems inappropriate, with its implication that this situation is temporary and/or unexpected.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The molecular era for population genetics can be said to date from 1966 following the studies of Lewontin and Hubby in Drosophila and Harris in humans.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Using protein electrophoresis, these authors showed that around one third of loci must be 'polymorphic', having some genetic differences between individuals in the population.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Given the large number of loci in the genome and the limited amount of recombination, it followed that there must be many very closely linked polymorphic loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Subsequent DNA sequencing, e.g. the International HapMap Project has shown that protein studies considerably underestimate the amount of polymorphism.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] There will usually be thousands of genetic differences, titled Single Nucleotide Polymorphism or SNPs, within short regions of the genome.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Cases of zero or very low recombination must be common.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] A second important finding pertaining to LD was the realisation that LD can arise simply because of population structure.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Studies such as those of Robbins referred to above essentially assume an infinite population size.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Small population size, in particular, can lead to LD quite independently of any selection.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] It became clear that LD, rather than being rare and of secondary importance, must be widespread.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This has had enormous importance in diverse fields of human genetics and animal breeding.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] It means that any gene of importance is likely to be surrounded by DNA SNPs in high LD with the gene of interest.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The position of the gene may be unknown, but the position of all DNA SNPs is known exactly.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This has allowed the mapping of causal genes in human genetics, using Genome-wide association studies (GWAS).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] It has allowed DNA 'breeding values' to be used as predictors, leading to advances in animal and plant breeding.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Haplotype frequencies can be set out in the form of a table with **x** and **y** columns.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Allele *A* is given the value '1' and allele *a* the value '0' in the **x** column.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Gamete frequencies are of the form *gi*, summing to 1.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] which is equivalent to the LD coefficient, *D*, as defined above.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This LD measure was introduced by Sewall Wright and its use popularised by Hill and Robertson.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The above LD theory is based on haploid frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] In practice, direct observation of such frequencies is rarely possible, since in most species of interest only diploid genotypes can be observed.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Assumptions need to be made to infer haploid frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] A different approach to estimating LD from diploid frequencies is to calculate the covariance and correlation of frequencies, just as for haploid frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Gao et al show that the diploid covariance is the same as "Burrows' composite LD measure".
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The table below shows *x* and *y* values for diploid genotypes.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] It also shows the expected frequencies on the assumption of random mating.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Normalising by the variances, the factor 2 cancels out.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Surprisingly, this is identical to the haploid LD correlation *rAB*.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The result is, as mentioned above, an expectation based on the assumption of random mating.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If the deviation from random mating is expressed in terms of the inbreeding coefficient *F*, the expected frequency of *AABB* homozygotes is equal to (1-*F*)*g*12 + *Fg*1, the expected frequency of non-homozygotes such as *AABb* is equal to (1-*F*)*g*1*g*2 etc.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] For two biallelic loci, where *a* and *b* are the other alleles at these two loci, the restrictions are so strong that only one value of *D* is sufficient to represent all linkage disequilibrium relationships between these alleles.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Their relationships can be characterized as follows.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The sign of *D* in this case is chosen arbitrarily.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The magnitude of *D* is more important than the sign of *D* because the magnitude of *D* is representative of the degree of linkage disequilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] However, positive *D* value means that the gamete is more frequent than expected while negative means that the combination of these two alleles are less frequent than expected.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Linkage disequilibrium in asexual populations can be defined in a similar way in terms of population allele frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Furthermore, it is also possible to define linkage disequilibrium among three or more alleles, however these higher-order associations are not commonly used in practice.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The linkage disequilibrium D reflects both changes in the intensity of the linkage correlation and changes in gene frequency.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This poses an issue when comparing linkage disequilibrium between alleles with differing frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Normalization of linkage disequilibrium allows these alleles to be compared more easily.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The value of $D'$ will be within the range $-1\leq D'\leq 1$ .
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] When $-1\leq D'<0$ , the alleles are found less often than expected.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] When $0<D'\leq 1$ , the alleles are found more often than expected.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Note that $|D'|$ may be used in place of $D'$ when measuring how close two alleles are to linkage equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The value of $r^{2}$ will be within the range $0\leq r^{2}\leq 1$ .
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] When $r^{2}=0$ , there is no correlation between the pair.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] When $r^{2}=1$ , the correlation is either perfect positive or perfect negative according to the sign of r .
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Another alternative normalizes D by the product of two of the four allele frequencies when the two frequencies represent alleles from the same locus.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This allows comparison of asymmetry between a pair of loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This is often used in case-control studies where **B** is the locus containing a disease allele.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Similar to the d method, this alternative normalizes D by the product of two of the four allele frequencies when the two frequencies represent alleles from different loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The measures $r^{2}$ and $D'$ have limits to their ranges and do not range over all values of zero to one for all pairs of loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The maximum of $r^{2}$ depends on the allele frequencies at the two loci being compared and can only range fully from zero to one where either the allele frequencies at both loci are equal, $P_{A}=P_{B}$ where $D>0$ , or when the allele frequencies have the relationship $P_{A}=1-P_{B}$ when $D<0$ .
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] While $D'$ can always take a maximum value of 1, its minimum value for two loci is equal to $|r|$ for those loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Consider the haplotypes for two loci A and B with two alleles each—a two-loci, two-allele model.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Note that these are relative frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If the two loci and the alleles are independent from each other, then we would expect the frequency of each haplotype to be equal to the product of the frequencies of its corresponding alleles (e.g. $x_{11}=p_{1}q_{1}$ ).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Thus, if the loci were inherited independently, then $x_{11}=p_{1}q_{1}$ , so $D=0$ , and there is linkage equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] However, if the observed frequency of haplotype $A_{1}B_{1}$ were higher than what would be expected based on the individual frequencies of $A_{1}$ and $B_{1}$ then $x_{11}>p_{1}q_{1}$ , so $D>0$ , and there is positive linkage disequilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Conversely, if the observed frequency were lower, then $x_{11}<p_{1}q_{1}$ , $D<0$ , and there is negative linkage disequilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The following table illustrates the relationship between the haplotype frequencies and allele frequencies and D.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Additionally, we can normalize our data based on what we are trying to accomplish.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] For example, if we aim to create an association map in a case-control study, then we may use the d method due to its asymmetry.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If we are trying to find the probability that a given haplotype will descend in a population without being recombined by other haplotypes, then it may be better to use the ρ method.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] But for most scenarios, $r^{2}$ tends to be the most popular method due to the usefulness of the correlation coefficient in statistics.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] A couple examples of where $r^{2}$ may be very useful would include measuring the recombination rate in an evolving population, or detecting disease associations.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Using the notation above, $D=x_{11}-p_{1}q_{1}$ , we can demonstrate this convergence to zero as follows.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This follows because a fraction $(1-c)$ of the haplotypes in the offspring have not recombined, and are thus copies of a random haplotype in their parents.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] A fraction c have recombined these two loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] where D at the n -th generation is designated as $D_{n}$ .
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] If at some time we observe linkage disequilibrium, it will disappear in the future due to recombination.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] However, the smaller the distance between the two loci, the smaller will be the rate of convergence of D to zero.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Once linkage disequilibrium has been calculated for a dataset, a visualization method is often chosen to display the linkage disequilibrium to make it more easily understandable.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The most common method is to use a heatmap, where colors are used to indicate the loci with positive linkage disequilibrium, and linkage equilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This example displays the full heatmap, but because the heatmap is symmetrical across the diagonal (that is, the linkage disequilibrium between loci A and B is the same as between B and A), a triangular heatmap that shows the pairs only once is also commonly employed.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This method has the advantage of being easy to interpret, but it also cannot display information about other variables that may be of interest.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] More robust visualization options are also available, like the textile plot.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] In a textile plot, combinations of alleles at a certain loci can be linked with combinations of alleles at a different loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Each genotype (combination of alleles) is represented by a circle which has an area proportional to the frequency of that genotype, with a column for each loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Lines are drawn from each circle to the circles in the other column(s), and the thickness of the connecting line is proportional to the frequency that the two genotypes occur together.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Linkage disequilibrium is seen through the number of line crossings in the diagram, where a greater number of line crossings indicates a low linkage disequilibrium and fewer crossings indicate a high linkage disequilibrium.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Another visualization option is forests of hierarchical latent class models (FHLCM).
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] All loci are plotted along the top layer of the graph, and below this top layer, boxes representing latent variables are added with links to the top level.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] Lines connect the loci at the top level to the latent variables below, and the lower the level of the box that the loci are connected to, the greater the linkage disequilibrium and the smaller the distance between the loci.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] While this method does not have the same advantages of the textile plot, it does allow for the visualization of loci that are far apart without requiring the sequence to be rearranged, as is the case with the textile plot.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] This is not an exhaustive list of visualization methods, and multiple methods may be used to display a data set in order to give a better picture of the data based on the information that the researcher aims to highlight.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The International HapMap Project enables the study of LD in human populations online.
[src:population-genetics/linkage-disequilibrium] The Ensembl project integrates HapMap data with other genetic information from dbSNP.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetics was a vital ingredient in the emergence of the modern evolutionary synthesis.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Its primary founders were Sewall Wright, J.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Haldane and Ronald Fisher, who also laid the foundations for the related discipline of quantitative genetics.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Traditionally a highly mathematical discipline, modern population genetics encompasses theoretical, laboratory, and field work.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetic models are used both for statistical inference from DNA sequence data and for proof/disproof of concept.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This makes it appropriate for comparison to population genomics data.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetics began as a reconciliation of Mendelian inheritance and biostatistics models.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Natural selection will only cause evolution if there is enough genetic variation in a population.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Before the discovery of Mendelian genetics, one common hypothesis was blending inheritance.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] But with blending inheritance, genetic variance would be rapidly lost, making evolution by natural or sexual selection implausible.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The Hardy–Weinberg principle provides the solution to how variation is maintained in a population with Mendelian inheritance.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] According to this principle, the frequencies of alleles (variations in a gene) will remain constant in the absence of selection, mutation, migration and genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] : the black-bodied form of the peppered moth appeared in polluted areas.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The next key step was the work of the British biologist and statistician Ronald Fisher.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In a series of papers beginning in 1924, another British geneticist, J.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Haldane, worked out the mathematics of allele frequency change at a single gene locus under a broad range of conditions.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The American biologist Sewall Wright, who had a background in animal breeding experiments, focused on combinations of interacting genes, and the effects of inbreeding on small, relatively isolated populations that exhibited genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In 1932 Wright introduced the concept of an adaptive landscape and argued that genetic drift and inbreeding could drive a small, isolated sub-population away from an adaptive peak, allowing natural selection to drive it towards different adaptive peaks.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The work of Fisher, Haldane and Wright founded the discipline of population genetics.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This integrated natural selection with Mendelian genetics, which was the critical first step in developing a unified theory of how evolution worked.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] John Maynard Smith was Haldane's pupil, whilst W.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Hamilton was influenced by the writings of Fisher.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Price worked with both Hamilton and Maynard Smith.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] American Richard Lewontin and Japanese Motoo Kimura were influenced by Wright and Haldane.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The mathematics of population genetics were originally developed as the beginning of the modern synthesis.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Authors such as Beatty have asserted that population genetics defines the core of the modern synthesis.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] For the first few decades of the 20th century, most field naturalists continued to believe that Lamarckism and orthogenesis provided the best explanation for the complexity they observed in the living world.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] During the modern synthesis, these ideas were purged, and only evolutionary causes that could be expressed in the mathematical framework of population genetics were retained.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Consensus was reached as to which evolutionary factors might influence evolution, but not as to the relative importance of the various factors.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Theodosius Dobzhansky, a postdoctoral worker in T.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Morgan's lab, had been influenced by the work on genetic diversity by Russian geneticists such as Sergei Chetverikov.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] He helped to bridge the divide between the foundations of microevolution developed by the population geneticists and the patterns of macroevolution observed by field biologists, with his 1937 book *Genetics and the Origin of Species*.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Dobzhansky examined the genetic diversity of wild populations and showed that, contrary to the assumptions of the population geneticists, these populations had large amounts of genetic diversity, with marked differences between sub-populations.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The book also took the highly mathematical work of the population geneticists and put it into a more accessible form.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Many more biologists were influenced by population genetics via Dobzhansky than were able to read the highly mathematical works in the original.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Ford, the pioneer of ecological genetics, continued throughout the 1930s and 1940s to empirically demonstrate the power of selection due to ecological factors including the ability to maintain genetic diversity through genetic polymorphisms such as human blood types.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Ford's work, in collaboration with Fisher, contributed to a shift in emphasis during the modern synthesis towards natural selection as the dominant force.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The original, modern synthesis view of population genetics assumes that mutations provide ample raw material, and focuses only on the change in frequency of alleles within populations.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The main processes influencing allele frequencies are natural selection, genetic drift, gene flow and recurrent mutation.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Fisher and Wright had some fundamental disagreements about the relative roles of selection and drift.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The availability of molecular data on all genetic differences led to the neutral theory of molecular evolution.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In this view, many mutations are deleterious and so never observed, and most of the remainder are neutral, i.e. are not under selection.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] With the fate of each neutral mutation left to chance (genetic drift), the direction of evolutionary change is driven by which mutations occur, and so cannot be captured by models of change in the frequency of (existing) alleles alone.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The origin-fixation view of population genetics generalizes this approach beyond strictly neutral mutations, and sees the rate at which a particular change happens as the product of the mutation rate and the fixation probability.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Natural selection, which includes sexual selection, is the fact that some traits make it more likely for an organism to survive and reproduce.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetics describes natural selection by defining fitness as a propensity or probability of survival and reproduction in a particular environment.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The fitness is normally given by the symbol **w**=1-**s** where **s** is the selection coefficient.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Natural selection acts on phenotypes, so population genetic models assume relatively simple relationships to predict the phenotype and hence fitness from the allele at one or a small number of loci.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In this way, natural selection converts differences in the fitness of individuals with different phenotypes into changes in allele frequency in a population over successive generations.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Before the advent of population genetics, many biologists doubted that small differences in fitness were sufficient to make a large difference to evolution.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population geneticists addressed this concern in part by comparing selection to genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Selection can overcome genetic drift when **s** is greater than 1 divided by the effective population size.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] When this criterion is met, the probability that a new advantageous mutant becomes fixed is approximately equal to **2s**.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The time until fixation of such an allele is approximately $(2log(sN)+\gamma )/s$ .
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Dominance means that the phenotypic and/or fitness effect of one allele at a locus depends on which allele is present in the second copy for that locus.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] s is the selection coefficient and h is the dominance coefficient.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Epistasis means that the phenotypic and/or fitness effect of an allele at one locus depends on which alleles are present at other loci.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Selection does not act on a single locus, but on a phenotype that arises through development from a complete genotype.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] However, many population genetics models of sexual species are "single locus" models, where the fitness of an individual is calculated as the product of the contributions from each of its loci—effectively assuming no epistasis.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In fact, the genotype to fitness landscape is more complex.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetics must either model this complexity in detail, or capture it by some simpler average rule.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Empirically, beneficial mutations tend to have a smaller fitness benefit when added to a genetic background that already has high fitness: this is known as diminishing returns epistasis.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] When deleterious mutations also have a smaller fitness effect on high fitness backgrounds, this is known as "synergistic epistasis".
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] However, the effect of deleterious mutations tends on average to be very close to multiplicative, or can even show the opposite pattern, known as "antagonistic epistasis".
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Synergistic epistasis is central to some theories of the purging of mutation load and to the evolution of sexual reproduction.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The genetic process of mutation takes place within an individual, resulting in heritable changes to the genetic material.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Single-nucleotide changes are frequently the most common type of mutation, but many other types of mutation are possible, and they occur at widely varying rates that may show systematic asymmetries or biases (mutation bias).
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Mutations can involve large sections of DNA becoming duplicated, usually through genetic recombination.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This leads to copy-number variation within a population.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Duplications are a major source of raw material for evolving new genes.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Other types of mutation occasionally create new genes from previously noncoding DNA.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In the distribution of fitness effects (DFE) for new mutations, only a minority of mutations are beneficial.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Mutations with gross effects are typically deleterious.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Studies in the fly *Drosophila melanogaster* suggest that if a mutation changes a protein produced by a gene, this will probably be harmful, with about 70 percent of these mutations having damaging effects, and the remainder being either neutral or weakly beneficial.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This biological process of mutation is represented in population-genetic models in one of two ways, either as a deterministic pressure of recurrent mutation on allele frequencies, or a source of variation.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In deterministic theory, evolution begins with a predetermined set of alleles and proceeds by shifts in continuous frequencies, as if the population is infinite.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The occurrence of mutations in individuals is represented by a population-level "force" or "pressure" of mutation, i.e., the force of innumerable events of mutation with a scaled magnitude u applied to shifting frequencies f(A1) to f(A2).
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] For instance, in the classic mutation–selection balance model, the force of mutation pressure pushes the frequency of an allele upward, and selection against its deleterious effects pushes the frequency downward, so that a balance is reached at equilibrium, given (in the simplest case) by f = u/s.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This concept of mutation pressure is mostly useful for considering the implications of deleterious mutation, such as the mutation load and its implications for the evolution of the mutation rate.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Transformation of populations by mutation pressure is unlikely.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Haldane argued that it would require high mutation rates unopposed by selection, and Kimura concluded even more pessimistically that even this was unlikely, as the process would take too long (see evolution by mutation pressure).
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] However, evolution by mutation pressure is possible under some circumstances and has long been suggested as a possible cause for the loss of unused traits.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] For example, pigments are no longer useful when animals live in the darkness of caves, and tend to be lost.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] An experimental example involves the loss of sporulation in experimental populations of *B. subtilis*.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Sporulation is a complex trait encoded by many loci, such that the mutation rate for loss of the trait was estimated as an unusually high value, $\mu =0.003$ .
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Loss of sporulation in this case can occur by recurrent mutation, without requiring selection for the loss of sporulation ability.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] When there is no selection for loss of function, the speed at which loss evolves depends more on the mutation rate than it does on the effective population size, indicating that it is driven more by mutation than by genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The role of mutation as a source of novelty is different from these classical models of mutation pressure.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] That is, the spectrum of mutation may become very important, particularly mutation biases, predictable differences in the rates of occurrence for different types of mutations, because bias in the introduction of variation can impose biases on the course of evolution.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Mutation plays a key role in other classical and recent theories including Muller's ratchet, subfunctionalization, Eigen's concept of an error catastrophe and Lynch's mutational hazard hypothesis.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The effect of genetic drift is larger for alleles present in few copies than when an allele is present in many copies.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The population genetics of genetic drift are described using either branching processes or a diffusion equation describing changes in allele frequency.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] These approaches are usually applied to the Wright-Fisher and Moran models of population genetics.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Ronald Fisher held the view that genetic drift plays at the most a minor role in evolution, and this remained the dominant view for several decades.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] No population genetics perspective have ever given genetic drift a central role by itself, but some have made genetic drift important in combination with another non-selective force.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The shifting balance theory of Sewall Wright held that the combination of population structure and genetic drift was important.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Motoo Kimura's neutral theory of molecular evolution claims that most genetic differences within and between populations are caused by the combination of neutral mutations and genetic drift.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The role of genetic drift by means of sampling error in evolution has been criticized by John H Gillespie and Will Provine, who argue that selection on linked sites is a more important stochastic force, doing the work traditionally ascribed to genetic drift by means of sampling error.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Because of physical barriers to migration, along with the limited tendency for individuals to move or spread (vagility), and tendency to remain or come back to natal place (philopatry), natural populations rarely all interbreed as may be assumed in theoretical random models (panmixy).
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] There is usually a geographic range within which individuals are more closely related to one another than those randomly selected from the general population.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This is described as the extent to which a population is genetically structured.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Genetic structuring can be caused by migration due to historical climate change, species range expansion or current availability of habitat.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Gene flow is hindered by mountain ranges, oceans and deserts or even human-made structures such as the Great Wall of China, which has hindered the flow of plant genes.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Gene flow is the exchange of genes between populations or species, breaking down the structure.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Examples of gene flow within a species include the migration and then breeding of organisms, or the exchange of pollen.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Gene transfer between species includes the formation of hybrid organisms and horizontal gene transfer.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetic models can be used to identify which populations show significant genetic isolation from one another, and to reconstruct their history.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Subjecting a population to isolation leads to inbreeding depression.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Migration into a population can introduce new genetic variants, potentially contributing to evolutionary rescue.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] If a significant proportion of individuals or gametes migrate, it can also change allele frequencies, e.g. giving rise to migration load.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In the presence of gene flow, other barriers to hybridization between two diverging populations of an outcrossing species are required for the populations to become new species.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Horizontal gene transfer is the transfer of genetic material from one organism to another organism that is not its offspring; this is most common among prokaryotes.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In medicine, this contributes to the spread of antibiotic resistance, as when one bacteria acquires resistance genes it can rapidly transfer them to other species.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Horizontal transfer of genes from bacteria to eukaryotes such as the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* and the adzuki bean beetle *Callosobruchus chinensis* may also have occurred.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] An example of larger-scale transfers are the eukaryotic bdelloid rotifers, which appear to have received a range of genes from bacteria, fungi, and plants.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Viruses can also carry DNA between organisms, allowing transfer of genes even across biological domains.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Large-scale gene transfer has also occurred between the ancestors of eukaryotic cells and prokaryotes, during the acquisition of chloroplasts and mitochondria.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] If all genes are in linkage equilibrium, the effect of an allele at one locus can be averaged across the gene pool at other loci.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In reality, one allele is frequently found in linkage disequilibrium with genes at other loci, especially with genes located nearby on the same chromosome.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Recombination breaks up this linkage disequilibrium too slowly to avoid genetic hitchhiking, where an allele at one locus rises to high frequency because it is linked to an allele under selection at a nearby locus.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Linkage also slows down the rate of adaptation, even in sexual populations.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The effect of linkage disequilibrium in slowing down the rate of adaptive evolution arises from a combination of the Hill–Robertson effect (delays in bringing beneficial mutations together) and background selection (delays in separating beneficial mutations from deleterious hitchhikers).
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Linkage is a problem for population genetic models that treat one gene locus at a time.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] It can, however, be exploited as a method for detecting the action of natural selection via selective sweeps.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In the extreme case of an asexual population, linkage is complete, and population genetic equations can be derived and solved in terms of a travelling wave of genotype frequencies along a simple fitness landscape.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Most microbes, such as bacteria, are asexual.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The population genetics of their adaptation have two contrasting regimes.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] When the product of the beneficial mutation rate and population size is small, asexual populations follow a "successional regime" of origin-fixation dynamics, with adaptation rate strongly dependent on this product.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] When the product is much larger, asexual populations follow a "concurrent mutations" regime with adaptation rate less dependent on the product, characterized by clonal interference and the appearance of a new beneficial mutation before the last one has fixed.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Neutral theory predicts that the level of nucleotide diversity in a population will be proportional to the product of the population size and the neutral mutation rate.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The fact that levels of genetic diversity vary much less than population sizes do is known as the "paradox of variation".
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] While high levels of genetic diversity were one of the original arguments in favor of neutral theory, the paradox of variation has been one of the strongest arguments against neutral theory.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] It is clear that levels of genetic diversity vary greatly within a species as a function of local recombination rate, due to both genetic hitchhiking and background selection.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Most current solutions to the paradox of variation invoke some level of selection at linked sites.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] For example, one analysis suggests that larger populations have more selective sweeps, which remove more neutral genetic diversity.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] A negative correlation between mutation rate and population size may also contribute.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Life history affects genetic diversity more than population history does, e.g. r-strategists have more genetic diversity.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Population genetics models are used to infer which genes are undergoing selection.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] One common approach is to look for regions of high linkage disequilibrium and low genetic variance along the chromosome, to detect recent selective sweeps.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] A second common approach is the McDonald–Kreitman test which compares the amount of variation within a species (polymorphism) to the divergence between species (substitutions) at two types of sites; one assumed to be neutral.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Typically, synonymous sites are assumed to be neutral.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Genes undergoing positive selection have an excess of divergent sites relative to polymorphic sites.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The test can also be used to obtain a genome-wide estimate of the proportion of substitutions that are fixed by positive selection, α.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] According to the neutral theory of molecular evolution, this number should be near zero.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] High numbers have therefore been interpreted as a genome-wide falsification of neutral theory.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The simplest test for population structure in a sexually reproducing, diploid species, is to see whether genotype frequencies follow Hardy-Weinberg proportions as a function of allele frequencies.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] For example, in the simplest case of a single locus with two alleles denoted **A** and **a** at frequencies *p* and *q*, random mating predicts freq(**AA**) = *p*2 for the **AA** homozygotes, freq(**aa**) = *q*2 for the **aa** homozygotes, and freq(**Aa**) = 2*pq* for the heterozygotes.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] In the absence of population structure, Hardy-Weinberg proportions are reached within 1–2 generations of random mating.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] More typically, there is an excess of homozygotes, indicative of population structure.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The extent of this excess can be quantified as the inbreeding coefficient, F.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Individuals can be clustered into *K* subpopulations.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] The degree of population structure can then be calculated using FST, which is a measure of the proportion of genetic variance that can be explained by population structure.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Genetic population structure can then be related to geographic structure, and genetic admixture can be detected.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Coalescent theory relates genetic diversity in a sample to demographic history of the population from which it was taken.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] It normally assumes neutrality, and so sequences from more neutrally evolving portions of genomes are therefore selected for such analyses.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] It can be used to infer the relationships between species (phylogenetics), as well as the population structure, demographic history (e.g. population bottlenecks, population growth), biological dispersal, source–sink dynamics and introgression within a species.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Another approach to demographic inference relies on the allele frequency spectrum.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] For example, most mutations are deleterious, so the optimal mutation rate for a species may be a trade-off between the damage from a high deleterious mutation rate and the metabolic costs of maintaining systems to reduce the mutation rate, such as DNA repair enzymes.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] One important aspect of such models is that selection is only strong enough to purge deleterious mutations and hence overpower mutational bias towards degradation if the selection coefficient s is greater than the inverse of the effective population size.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] This is known as the drift barrier and is related to the nearly neutral theory of molecular evolution.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] Drift barrier theory predicts that species with large effective population sizes will have highly streamlined, efficient genetic systems, while those with small population sizes will have bloated and complex genomes containing for example introns and transposable elements.
[src:population-genetics/population-genetics] However, somewhat paradoxically, species with large population sizes might be so tolerant to the consequences of certain types of errors that they evolve higher error rates, e.g. in transcription and translation, than small populations.
